<TITLE> River traffic suspended </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 17 (bdnews24.com)The looming cyclonic storm 'Bijli' forced authorities Friday to suspend the movement of water transport vehicles on a number of inland water routes in the coastal region. The Bangladesh Inland Water Transport Authority has suspended movements of passenger ferries, cargo vessels and other water transport vehicles in Chandpur, Barisal, Patuakhali, Bhola and Noakhali districts. bdnews24.com correspondents from coastal districts report that the inland water routes have been without transport since Friday morning. An officer of Chandpur River Port said the routes will be remaining snapped until further notice. Several thousands volunteers from Bangladesh Red Crescent have put on alert in case evacuations are called. Warning signal 7 has been raised for the main port Chittagong and fishing boats have been ordered back to shore as the season's first cyclonic storm, "Bijli" packing winds up to 90 kph was closing in on southwestern shorelines. The cyclonic storm over North Bay moved slightly northeastwards and now lies over the same area. It was centred at 3pm about 345 kms southwest of Chittagong port, 315 kms southwest of Cox's Bazar port and 200 kms south-southwest of Mongla port. The Meteorology Department said in a special weather bulletin it was likely to intensify further and move in a northeasterly direction and may cross Barisal-Chittagong coast near Meghna estuary by mid night to night. Cox's Bazaar and Mongla ports were asked to keep hoisted danger signal 6 and 5, respectively. Storms are graded with signals ranging from 1 to 10, and authorities start major preparations when the signal is raised to five or beyond. bdnews24.co
